In the spirit of wiki's, contributing is at the heart of all knowledge here. With every contribution does this book get better and more diverse. To contribute, all you need to do is follow the conventions listed below.

== Definitions ==
<!--
=== Definition or glossary pages ===
Definitions in a particular subject should be found on a page of their own, for example:

 IB/Group 4/Computer Science/'''Definitions'''

i.e.

 IB/''Group''/''Subject''/'''Definitions'''

The definitions page should be ordered alphabetically using a alphabetic table of contents. A standard template for definition pages is:

 <nowiki>{{DISPLAYTITLE:Definitions}}{{CompactTOC8}}[[Category:IB/Definitions]]
===A===
===B===
===...===
===Y===
===Z===</nowiki>

=== Adding definitions ===
To add a definition to the definition page, simply use the following markup:

 &#123;&#123;IB/Define|'''Term'''|<nowiki><onlyinclude></nowiki>'''The full definition of the term.'''<nowiki><onlyinclude></nowiki>&#125;&#125;

Notice that inside the definition there are html tags for <code><nowiki><onlyinclude></nowiki></code>. This is important in abstracting the definition for later display.

The new definition markup will produce something along the lines of:
{{IB/Define|Term|<onlyinclude>The full definition of the term.<onlyinclude>}}

=== Using definitions ===
To display a definition in the body of some text you can use the following:
 &#123;&#123;IB/Definition|namespace|'''Term'''|float&#125;&#125;

The <code>namespace</code> of the definition is an important attribute. It points the template to the correct definitions page, and for this reason it is the first attribute. The namespace must be the path to the subject, i.e. <code>''group''/''subject''</code>. The <code>'''Term'''</code> is <u>case sensitive</u> and represents the definition found on the definition page. The <code>float</code> is optional and allows you to choose where the definition boxes lies; either on the <code>left</code> or <code>right</code>.

For example, this:

 &#123;&#123;IB/Definition|Group 4/Computer Science|Arithmetic/Logic Unit (ALU)&#125;&#125;

produces:

{{IB/Definition|Group 4/Computer Science|Absolute path}}
-->

